Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *Frontend Engineer* position with *Fauna Robotics*. I bring over three years of professional experience building production-grade web applications, real-time systems, and internal developer tools, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered systems that directly reflect the demands of building real-time, low-latency frontend interfaces for complex hardware-adjacent platforms. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I architected a TypeScript-based interaction layer exposing 1,000+ platform endpoints through validated REST API contracts — owning the deliverable end-to-end, from API contract design through real-time execution feedback. I optimized frontend performance to achieve low-latency, real-time interactions, reducing end-to-end latency by 60% and API costs by 50% through targeted concurrency and routing improvements. I also built a suite of internal developer tools — API-aware templates, SDK patterns, and code-generation workflows — that directly accelerated platform integration across the engineering team. Prior to Sperse, at Qualitest, I contributed to a React-based Identity & Access Management platform supporting thousands of users across 30+ applications, delivering a responsive, cross-browser web application backed by AWS infrastructure, and developed internal tools using AWS Step Functions to automate long-running operational workflows. Together, these roles have prepared me to contribute meaningfully to Fauna's core engineering responsibilities around real-time data visualization, frontend performance, and internal tooling that accelerates development and operations workflows.

My research and personal project work demonstrate deep engagement with the real-time visualization and control interface challenges central to this role. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I built tooling for model telemetry and real-time performance visualization on GPU clusters — a direct analogue to the robotics telemetry dashboards this role requires. My open-source project, Dark Factory, pushes this further: it is a real-time control interface for AI CLI orchestration with event-driven loops that broadcast live updates via WebSocket-style signaling, eliminating polling overhead and targeting the low-latency responsiveness that Fauna's robot control interfaces demand. Beyond building these systems, I led workshops on GPU programming and AI agent development for 50+ students, honing the cross-functional technical communication skills that mirror the engineering discipline and collaborative culture Fauna values — working across robotics, backend, and product teams to design APIs and data models that make robot interactions feel responsive and intuitive.

I have always been passionate about making powerful technology accessible and genuinely delightful for everyday users, and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of Fauna Robotics' mission to build capable, safe, and fun robots for everyone. The goal of making robots people actually want to live and interact with in everyday human spaces is exactly the kind of frontier work I want to pursue. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

